1242310: Do not issue ueber certs that expire after 2050 RFC 5280 states in section 4125:    CAs conforming to this profile MUST always encode certificate    validity dates through the year 2049 as UTCTime certificate validity    dates in 2050 or later MUST be encoded as GeneralizedTime    Conforming applications MUST be able to process validity dates that    are encoded in either UTCTime or GeneralizedTimeBut currently python-rhsm is parsing certificates with either M2Cryptoor a custom C binding (certificatec) to OpenSSLs x509v3 (so that we can accessthe raw octets in the custom X509 extensions used in version 3 entitlementcertificates)  Both M2Crypto and our binding contain code that automaticallyconverts the Not After time into a UTCTime  The conversion succeeds but thevalue of the resultant object is something like Bad time value which whenfed into Pythons datetime causes an exceptionThe quick fix is to not issue certificates that expire after January 1 2050

Awood/client refactor Ruby bindings for the Candlepin REST APIYou will need to run a bundle install before attempting to use or test the bindingsUnit tests are provided for the bindings and can be run from the server/client/ruby/test directory with /test_candlepinrb  (If you are using an older version of OpenSSL the tests will print some annoying warning messages  Those can be suppressed by running ruby -W0 /test_candlepinrb)One unit test is currently failing (updates an owner pool) due to an issue within Candlepin itselfI am a little unhappy with the length of the candelpinrb file  We could split up the bindings into one resource per file and source each resources bindings in candlepinrb but given how interrelated some of the different resources are I dont know that having multiple source files makes life any easier  Any thoughts on the organization are appreciated

Several improvements made to the CP2 migration task - Created a new abstract classes LiquibaseCustomTask and  LiquibaseCustomTaskWrapper which contains common functionality  many custom tasks utilize- Updated the per-org products and pool-type upgrade tasks to use  the new abstract superclass- Began splitting the per-org products update task into two tasks:  one to do the initial migration of data without affecting existing  data and another to do destructive changes to shared tables- The first part of the per-org products task can be run repeatedly- Log output has been further improved- Migration now prefetches content and products to cut down on  the number of per-org queries- Logging has been updated to be slightly more friendly- The setNull patch for Oracle has been improved to only use the  VARCHAR type when the database actually appears to be Oracle- The per-org products migration now uses bulk-inserts where applicable to  cut down on the amount of individual queries being run- Fixed several logging mismatches from the reversion away from the  migrate + update prototype- Unique checks are now also temporarily disabled during migration on  MySQL

Storage Band Implementation Backport to candlepin-0952 Implemented storage band counting Each entitlementwill equate to 1TB of coverage and marketing productswill use the multiplier such that sub quantity purchased* multiplier will yeild pool quantity (total capacity in TB)For example:pool_quanity  sub_qty_bought * (storage_band_attr * multiplier)              1 * (1 * 256)              256The resulting pool will have a quantity of 256 which cancover 256TB of storageThe rules will calculate a systems coverage based on abandstorageusage factConsider a system is using 128TB:- a quantity of 128 entitlements will cover the system (green)- a quantity  128 entitlements will partially cover the  system (yellow)- no entitlements (red)Marketing Product (requirements)---------------------------------The marketing product should define a multiplier that is equalto the total capacity in TBs It must be stackable and mustdefine the storage_band attribute (should be set to 1)- stacking_id: product_stack_id- mutli-entitlement: yes- storage_band: 1Consumer Requirements-------------------------The consumer must have the bandstorageusage fact set tothe total TB that it is usingNOTE: If this fact is not set the rules will assume a value      of 1TB- bandstorageusage: 128

Port Developer Subscriptions from master to 0951 This patch backports the developer subscription feature from themaster branch This is a net new commit since the code in masterwas added in a bunch of different commits and the merge was notvery smoothIn hosted mode a developer subscription will be granted to anyconsumer during autobind that will cover all of the consumersinstalled products An owner must have and active entitlement anda match must be made on the dev_sku specified by the consumerin order for the entitlement to be granted The developerentitlement comes from a special pool that is createdfor that consumer only and will be deleted along with theentitlement on manual removal or expiry Multiple runs of theauto-attach process that detect a change in coverage will causethe entitlement/pool to be removed and a new one created Theduration of the entitlement/pool will be the consumer registrationdate + expires_after duration attribute on the dev_sku product

Truncate timestamps on serialization MySQL does not support milliseconds on time stamps This has caused numerous issues with our spec tests This PR removes milliseconds of Date objects on serialization The dates are serialized to ISO 8601 format less the fractional seconds This is done on serialization by a custom date serializer to ensure no dates are missed This change fixes the broken unbind test in master (against MySQL) as well as includes fixes for two spec tests that required millisecondsI have checked python-rhsm nothing there seems to be relying on the presence of milliseconds and as the new format is still ISO 8601 compliant seems to be well tolerated by pythons built-in time/datetime/timedelta functionality As this would affect all clients and is not configurable it would definitely be worth it to have a second or even third set of eyes verify that nothing in python-rhsm breaks as a result of the removal of milliseconds from the serialized datesThe removal of milliseconds would save a lot of trouble for supporting MySQL that being said we do lose the millisecond level of precision (not sure if we really need it anyways)

1269045: Gutterball DB Growth Fix **ONCE REVIEW IS DONE DO NOT MERGE RIGHT AWAY**Im debating whether I will squash some of these commits Either way Ill have to tag commit message with the BZ#https://bugzillaredhatcom/show_bugcgiid1269045Also this PR is lacking test coverage due to time constraints I dont like this but Ill try and get something in while waiting for feedback from the review**Pull Request Details**Changed event new/oldentity column type to mediumtextso that large objects will not be used by the databaseUsing Lobs made hibernate use large object storage whichcaused disk space cleanup issues with postgres andwould leave the large objects around even after an eventrecord was deletedUsing mediumtext in hibernate and in liquibase allows storingstrings of 16MB (size limited text column for postgres) and should beplenty of space to store our event JSONEvents that are not handled will not be stored When handling events the JSON for Eventnew/oldEntity will only be stored until the event has been fully processed at which point it is nullifiedIve put in a quick and easy event cleaning task We can turn this into a framework later or replace with quartz Just wanted something in place to do some automatic cleanupI also did a column rename as it was causing issues in mysql**Some Things To Test**1 Please make sure to test the DB upgrade with events in the DB2 Make sure that existing events are cleaned out Note though that there is no automatic cleanup for large objects -- this may have to be a manual step as vacuum_lo tool is part of another package which may not be installed May have to provide steps to clean this up

Use a logical AND when using  pool-based searching criteria Assume SystemA is subscribed to SKUs p1 and p2  SystemB issubscribed to p1 only  In the previous implementation a request toPOST /owners/my_org/consumersskup1&skup2would yield [SystemA SystemB SystemA] since SystemA has both p1 andp2This patch changes that behavior so that the new result set would be[SystemA]See https://bugzillaredhatcom/show_bugcgiid1252145

1256926: Fixed Pool match filter query When using match parameters while listing available poolshibernate would return a partially initialized list ofpool objects when matching on a collection of sub objectsFor example if the match filter matched on 1 of 4 providedproducts only the matched provided product would be loadedin the Pools collection Only a hibernate refresh wouldbring the remainder in after the initial lookupThis patch changes the query to use correlated subqueriesinstead of left outer joins which works around the partialcollection issueI tried implementing a unit test for the curator butwasnt able to reproduce I have a hunch that HSQLDBmay be dealing with joins a little differently thanpostgres A spec test easily reproduced this issuehttps://bugzillaredhatcom/show_bugcgiid1256926

1263474: Standalone candlepin now returns the expected error message … …and codeWhen we removed the DefaultSubscriptionServiceAdapter the activateSubscription method of its replacement (ImportSubscriptionServiceAdapter) became a no op This causes a success response code to be sent to subscription manager with no content in the body As subscription manager at this time has no default message to display this resulted in no feedback being displayed to the userBZ: https://bugzillaredhatcom/show_bugcgiid1263474

Persist reporter id for Hypervisor checkins While an owner can have multiple hypervisor - guest mapping reporters Assumption is that at a given time only one reporter reports hypervisor mappings for a particular hypervisor of an owner This PR ensures that we:* persist if reporter id is available in the request else ignore* update if reporter id changed for the hypervisor* warn if a hypervisors reporter changed* dont warn if a reporter id was not set in the first place ( to avoid excessive warnings when this version first hits production )

Revert consumer/hypervisor last check-in tables This was intended to help reduce lock wait timeouts by removing contention oncp_consumerlastcheckin However we later discovered the performance impact wasjust too great as the size of the tables grew and unfortunately the work has tobe revertedThis was only fixing a symptom and not the underlying cause so that will have to be dealt with instead Recent changes may help reduce the long transactions that caused this in any caseUpgrade script is included to revert the values back to the max in the db at the timeQuartz will also have to be updated to remove refs to the jobs that are beingremoved In ITs case this will need to be done manually as their quartz tablesare in a separate databaseNOTE: if you attempt to upgrade a pre-existing mysql db with this it will fail Im treating the mysql dbms as if it were IT here as that is our only pre-existing mysql deployment I dont want them to run liquibase and get SQL they cant run (because their quartz tables are in another db) So upgrade is only provided for postgresql otherwise it assumes youre doing a fresh db deploy and dont have quartz jobs laying around

Revert Wrap all REST API requests in a transaction This feature was found to cause a massive memory leak which would surface underheavy load The 52a51af8 commit specifically is the point where the memorystarts to degrade Before this change used PS old gen would peak at about200mb after this change it will climb up to 26gbMay be possible to re-introduce this functionality once the interceptor isfixed to not leak memoryKept one portion of the reverted commits to not modify a live hibernate objectin UserResource when listing roles (as this was generally dangerous)This reverts commit 78581503e7f9dad531ef047668099a15d365d3bfThis reverts commit 37c0207a91050a5c6f9dce439417b787dc2177fdThis reverts commit 3628df5902413c57dea30aca6bc3c4cd569d0fc1This reverts commit 52a51af8c0696ba304521a8ed21f2d7f647ca109

Storage band implementation Implemented storage band counting Each entitlementwill equate to 1TB of coverage and marketing productswill use the multiplier such that sub quantity purchased* multiplier will yeild pool quantity (total capacity in TB)For example:pool_quanity  sub_qty_bought * (storage_band_attr * multiplier)              1 * (1 * 256)              256The resulting pool will have a quantity of 256 which cancover 256TB of storageThe rules will calculate a systems coverage based on abandstorageusage factConsider a system is using 128TB:- a quantity of 128 entitlements will cover the system (green)- a quantity  128 entitlements will partially cover the  system (yellow)- no entitlements (red)Marketing Product (requirements)---------------------------------The marketing product should define a multiplier that is equalto the total capacity in TBs It must be stackable and mustdefine the storage_band attribute (should be set to 1)- stacking_id: product_stack_id- mutli-entitlement: yes- storage_band: 1Consumer Requirements-------------------------The consumer must have the bandstorageusage fact set tothe total TB that it is usingNOTE: If this fact is not set the rules will assume a value      of 1TB- bandstorageusage: 128

Push migration detection from virt-who checkin to system checkin The lookup for the host to have most recently reported every guest UUID in avirt-who checkin was showing up as a major performance bottleneck exposing thefact that there are virt-who deployments of far larger size than anything weanticipatedWhen reporting thousands of guest IDs into orgs with tens of thousands alreadythere the performance very rapidly degrades beyond 60 second timeouts andcontinues to scale up linearly as new guest IDs are addedThe check was done during virt-who checkins to detect migration revokeentitlements restricted to the previous host and auto-heal if necessaryWe realized however that (a) most guest IDs never become registered consumersand (b) this behavior is causing bugs in revoking entitlements that the guestsystems are still attempting to useInstead we push the logic to system check-in time when fetching entitlementscerts or serials similar to when we regenerate dirty entitlements Thiseliminates all the wasted computation on guest IDs that never become consumersand the query becomes a small search for a guest UUID rather than thousands allat once

Reduce database chatter in GET /status This looks like it might be the largest chunk of processing our app does inprod Client makes ample use of this but IT also uses it as a health checkFirst step drops querying of rules version and source instead we set these onthe provider singleton whenever we recompile rules (ie they changed) The twoplaces they can change (rules upload and import) are updated to immediatelyrecompile rather than wait for someone to attempt to use themIdeally wed have dropped all db connectivity from the class but unfortunatelywe need to know if the db loses its connection so IT can drop the node fromrotation automatically Instead well reduce the query dramatically and justquery the updated timestampA nice future enhancement would be to catch db errors (all of them somewhere)and set some kind of flag once we see any

modifier content to be included inthe entitlement cert the consumer must be entitled to themodified product in one of the following ways:- consumer currently has an entitlement providing the modified product- the pool from which the entitlement cert is being generated from  provides the modified product- the pool from which the entitlement cert is being generated from  provides the modified Fix cross-compile issue with ConcurrentHashMap The Java 17 ConcurrentHashMap#keySet() returns a SetK while the Java18 version returns ConcurrentHashMapKeySetViewK  Since Java allows anoverridden method to return a sub-type of the parent methods returntype no compilation are raised  When we run the code on Java 17however it immediately fails since the ConcurrentHashMapKeySetViewclass is not availableOne solution is to compile against a 17 bootstrap classpath but since17 is not packaged for recent versions of Fedora we will work aroundthe issue by upcasting ConcurrentHashMaps to just MapsSee https://gistgithubcom/AlainODea/1375759b8720a3f9f094 for adetailed explanation

Official RHEL RPM Based Candlepin Containers This PR adds 4 containers for Candlepin on RHEL The two -base containers are RHEL 6 and 7 primed and ready for rpm installation but candlepin is not actually yet installed These use internal RH urls for builds so no actual RHEL content is in here but it should be fairly trivial to update the FROM lines to point to CentOS and build These are intended to be used by our automation to verify that rpms are installing and launching correctly During docker run a YUM_REPO environment variable must be passed to the startup script specifying the location to install candlepin fromThe candlepin-rhel6 and candlepin-rhel7 layer on top of the base variants and actually install Candlepin from internal RPM builds Likewise these URLs in the candlepinrepo files could be modified to point to public Candlepin reposcpdb and cpsetup are temporarily copied into the containers until I can get modifications into a proper tagged build of candlepin at which point these duplicates can be removedSee the READMEmkd for usage and more details on each

Products and Content are now org-specific Product and Content are now stored in a per-org/owner manner This change impacts several areas of the codebase starting from the object model to the way products/manifests are imported to how product/content data is queriedAdditionally several other changes were also made during this process:- Many model objects now reference Products and Content directly instead of requiring an additional lookup through a service adapter This allows several other model objects to also be referenced directly on their logical parents Primarily product and pool attributes now exist entirely on products (as pools just use a product for their base info)- Subscriptions have been almost entirely removed Use of the Subscription and the SubscriptionServiceAdapter/SubscriptionCurator should be limited entirely to a small portion of the import process- Use of the service adapters as a whole should be minimized instead favouring the use of curators- ProductCache has been removed entirely- Changes to the API have been minimized but some calls now require an owner/org in addition to their pre-existing requirements- The refresh pools operation is a no-op in non-hosted environments- Some code which may now be dead has been commented out and left in place at least until it can be reviewed and verified to no longer be needed Additionally there are a handful of TODO tasks which may require more attention before merging

5x Bind Improvement for Large SKUs Eliminate a db lookup for the exact same SKU product being run twice per content set when generating entitlement certificates leading to substantial performance improvementsAlso includes a more minor fix to stop filtering the content twice This only saves a second or so but it was the next highest hit and completely unnecessaryUsing test SKU with ~2600 content sets bind time was 108 seconds After these changes were down to 22sThe latter patch is getting a bit messy because the V1 / V3 code split is messy and really needs a refactor Going to attempt to do this on 20 / per-org products branch and limit changes to this 09x stream so went with the messy but fast approach here

Alikins/1193803 manifest import speed [DO NOT MERGE] Wip/notes/etc on manifest import for referencehttps://bugzillaredhatcom/show_bugcgiid1193803Before:sat6 client timeout importing a manifest with employee skusThe ruby client times out after about 2 minutes but therequest itself continues for ~5 minutes ~2 minutes import Contents and Products (about a second each)~2 minutes generating new pools and subsThe tomcat thread running this was using 100% of one cpuMost of the time spent was in hibernate doing a huge amountof object comparisons to determine if everything in thelarge transaction is up to date Seehttp://stackoverflowcom/questions/10143880/hibernate-queries-much-slower-with-flushmode-auto-until-clear-is-calledfor one description of this hibernate issueNow:Takes about 12-14 seconds to do the manifest importChanges:- Build list of uniq contents and products to import then import them  Elliminates some unneeded duplication and skips a lot of create or  update logic Saves 10-20 seconds (This may be obsoleted by the  COMMIT change)- After creating new objects refresh the session so the latest version  is included in the session cache This eliminates a lot of the update  checking from the auto flush and improves content/product import  import alot The product/content import stage goes from ~120 seconds  to about 1-2 seconds total- Grab a reference to the EntityManager for the session and call  setFlushMode(FlushModeTypeCOMMIT) on it This prevents hibernate  needing to constantly check if every object is up to date and waits  until transaction commit to flush This cuts the pool/sub creation  and refresh portion from 2-3 minutes to approximately 10 seconds total- Experiemental: Remove the poolCuratorflush() in  CandlepinPoolManagerprocessPoolUpdates() The flush here seems to  defeat some of the gain of using COMMIT flush mode and removing it  seems to work and gains a few seconds on the above (~16 secs to ~12  secs) but is likely needed for prod or more active systems- Experimental: The hashCode for Product was changed to not depend   entirely on the product id as per  http://docsjbossorg/hibernate/orm/42/manual/en-US/html/ch13html#transactions-basics-identity  This seems to worth a little performance when apply over the above  (maybe a seconds worth in clock time but more noticable in profile  data) But Im unsure if this would break compatability- Unaddressed potential improvements:  - With the import down to ~12 seconds the time spent creating json  objects for the event queue become significant Mostly in  EventFactoryentityToJson() Since that is done before the object is  sent to the message bus and not async the manifest import process  blocks on it For the kind of large subscriptions a employee sku  manifest creates that accounts for ~4secs of the ~12 seconds of a  manifest import  - Some of these changes maybe applicable to the general refresh pools  case as well- Unaddressed potential issues  - Most testing was done with fresh db and one manifest import    Updating an import or concurrent imports were untested- General oddities  - manifest Guestid lock contention Very similar to the consumer last checkin PR from a few weeks ago this one aims to reduce lock contention on guest ID updatesPreviously every guest ID update wiped out all rows and recreated them for that host even if nothing changed This gave us an updated timestamp we could leverage for who most recently reported a guest ID It also gave us a pile of lock wait timeouts in heavily loaded environmentsInstead we now insert a timestamp into a new table every time we see a consumer update that contains guest IDs The max value in this table for a consumer is joined together with the guest IDs for that consumer so we can query who most recently reported the guest A job is included to periodically destroy old guest checkin timestamps

Eliminate Lock Contention on Consumer Last Check-In Time Problems surface in deployments with extremely high load Because we update the consumers row every time they authenticate any request running long can cause other requests to wait longer than mysqls 50 second limit trying to get the lock to update that rowTo work around this I introduced a new table for consumer check-in times The Consumers last checkin time is calculated as the max in the table for that consumerA job is included to run periodically (every 8 hours by default) and clean out all but the most recent row for each consumer In a really big deployment this could be well into the millions Multiple attempts were made to delete all but the most recent row for each consumer none would scale to that level and work on all dbs Instead we query checkins to be deleted in batches and delete them one chunk (30k) at a time until there are none leftEnd result should eliminate lock wait timeouts on cp_consumerlastcheckin because were now doing fresh inserts in each request rather than everyone trying to update the same row

Virt-Who Checkin Performance Improvements virt-who checkins are easily blowing past the 60 second timeout that will occur with both virt-who or subscription-manager Approx 150 hypervisors each with 15 guests is about enough to do it in my system this was taking around 50s Problem boiled down to looking up the host consumer record for every hypervisor record and then two more queries to lookup the guest consumer and its latest host for each guest ID on each hypervisorFixed by batching up the requests and passing them in memory so we lookup hypervisor consumers for all hypervisors in the checkin and similarly the guest and host consumers for all guest IDs These three large queries vs ~4500 small queries results in a close to 10x performance improvement (50 - 7s on my system with the sample data mentioned above)Added a DTO for managing the intricacies of virt UUID casing and endianness when mapping these to their consumer records

Fixed broken consumer status report query Postgres has a hard query parameter limit of 32767 Sincethe report query had been using an IN criteria of activeconsumer uuids once the active consumer uuid recordspassed the 32767 limit our query would breakThis produced a rather useless error of:orgpostgresqlutilPSQLException: This connection has been closedSwitching from criterialist() to criteriascroll() temporarilyproduced a better error presented itselfThe fix was to remove the IN clause and incorporate theactive check into the overall main query

Large Pool + Modifier Content Performance Improvements Individual commits have more details but two problems uncovered both related to modifier content which indicates that it modifies some other product ID If you have an entitlement for that product ID the content gets enabled if you dont we skip itIn some cases it was discovered that the single entitlement being granted had content which modifies another product ID also in the entitlement In this case we did the bind then immediately flagged the entitlement just created for regeneration the next time the system asked for entitlements/serials Thus a subscription-manager bind would actually generate the cert twice (25s a pop for this particular SKU)Second fix dramatically improves the performance when there are large numbers of content sets that modify product IDs but calculating the list of all product IDs the consumer is entitled to once instead of querying the database twice per content set per product that it appears on

1171781: Major performance improvements for list owner pools With large numbers of pools (~1600) and a consumer with many entitlements(~350) list owner pools was taking ~50s when filtering for pools applicablefor a specific consumerThe problem resulted from the use of two rules classes Entitlement andQuantity Each was called once per pool (1600 times) and serializing theconsumers entitlements each time (minus the actual entitlement certificateblob thankfully)Brought back an old approach for entitlement rules where we make one rules callto filter all pools This was backed out inc7d65e7a6eb9f485959facaf8b19d4a3577a409b for memory usage reasons but thosewere not spawned by any particular bug or error only observation In the abovescenario the JSON context is about 35mbPursued a similar approach for QuantityRules where we only make one call forall poolsEnd result is about 4s for the same list pools operation virtuallyindistinguishable from the API call without consumer filtering (no rules) Thetime is spent serializing the JSON response about 63mbThis PR is against the 0926-hotfix branch where we need to release this Ill merge it to master manually after and also bump the rules version in master again as this one is equal to what we have in master atm

Correctly re-fire failed jobs Previous implementation was looking to catch PersistenceException but the jobwere most in need of refires (refresh pools) watch catching all Exceptions andre-throwing as something else so as it stands it looks like the refiremechanism was not working correctly at least for this jobAdditionally we need to detect MySQL transient deadlock exceptions which needto be retried triggered frequently due to mysql gap locking on indexes justwith concurrent inserts We dont have MySQL driver in classpath so we need towatch out for SqlException as well as PersistenceException and try a refire ifeither occurrs Sadly this is showing up wrapped in a RuntimeException thusthe cause checking

Make it possible for CandlepinExceptions to not log stacktraces I know this probably seems like an odd change but we need the ability to disable the CandlepinExceptionMapper from logging at ERROR level and the full stacktrace for certain Exception types in this case UnauthorizedException I added a flag to the parent CandlepinException that defaults to the behaviour as it has always been Obviously for the vast majority of Exceptions we would want it logged as an ERROR with the full stacktraceWhen we throw the UnauthorizedException in our own adapter implementation we will disable this flag and take on the responsibility of making sure it is logged appropriately In our case we would be much happier with a single line WARN that does not include a stacktraceI am certainly open to suggestions if you have a better idea for how this could be achieved

Consumer Status Report: Result Set Size Error Fix Fixed an issue with the Consumer Status Report where an errorwould be thrown if the result set reached a certain sizeFirst query for the IDs of the latest compliance snapshotsand then do a final lookup by id using find The find methoddoes not have a data size limit here since it returns a DBcursor to the resultsWhile doing this is not that pretty it did not seem to havemuch of an impact on performance as a lookup by a set of IDsis pretty quickIndexes were also added to the consumer and compliance collectionshowever this did not seem to improve query performance all thatmuch

Request Transactions Original intention of the API was for a request to either fail or succeed and never make partial changes to the DB Over time this has been lost most likely with inconsistent use of where the transactional annotation is appliedTo remedy we will use an interceptor/invoker to automatically initiate a transaction on every REST API method Use of Transactional lower in the call stack will no-op as Guice always re-uses an open transaction rather than starting a new one Also included is an annotation for NonTransactional to avoid this behaviour which is required in one specific location where we import manifests but want to record that the import failed The error handling around this API call is extremely delicate so left alone for nowAlso fixed a bug exposed by the change where we modified a Hibernate object for display purposes to hide information which started being persisted to the DB once wrapped in a transaction

Ckozak/event refactor fix EventBuilder is more general:eventFactorygetEventBuilder(TargetPOOL TypeMODIFIED)    setOldEntity(old)    setNewEntity(updated)    buildEvent()Pros:* Easier to use* We dont have to write/maintain methods for every event type* More consistent event creation than writing individual methods* If were patching an existing object (like consumer) this makes it easy to take a snapshot of json before and after changes are made without passing around half-baked event objectsCons:* Doesnt enforce types  * ex: I can create a POOL event and give it a Consumer object  * We can keep a mapping of event target enum - Class in order to enforce this (although not using real types just throw exceptions if theyre mismatched)    * that would be the result of programmer error though

1113202: Add derived content to distributors ent cert For VDC subscriptions the host entitlements have nocontent This is whats getting exported to a distributorand stored as the upstream cert When a guest eventuallygoes to use an entitlement from its derived VDC poolthe upstream cert has no content on it preventing theguest from getting content it is entitled toThis patch generates VDC certificates differently if being grantedto a distributor and includes all content for both the parent andthe derived pools This will be the upstream certificate thatgets used to access content**Note**Tried testing this is a unit test but got tangled up in mocks It was a lot easier to test via spec Let me know if you feel strong enough that it should be unit tested in the service adapter

Efficient entitlement pool validation # Changes* Validate entire pools at once* No longer call the js rules validation for individual attributes* Support filtering lists of pools (only for listing pools no bulk binds etc)## The ProblemPrior to this patch running [EntitlementRules](https://githubcom/candlepin/candlepin/blob/candlepin-0910-1/src/main/java/org/candlepin/policy/js/entitlement/AbstractEntitlementRulesjava#L84-L105) passes through the javascript rules for each attribute (selected from a list of white-listed strings)For each pool we try to [look up a host consumer](https://githubcom/candlepin/candlepin/blob/candlepin-0910-1/src/main/java/org/candlepin/policy/js/entitlement/EntitlementRulesjava#L105-L109)When were listing pools for a consumer we only need to do that lookup once  Furthermore we might as well send the entire list into the rules at once##  CompatibilityUnless we are willing to rev the major version in rulesjs we need to make sure we dont break old candlepin servers that consume our exportsIve renamed all the validator methods and they must be passed a context and validation result  I wrote a [wrapper function generator](https://githubcom/candlepin/candlepin/blob/ae366725524e4c95e39fc740da6c8317d4db84b0/src/main/resources/rules/rulesjs#L1342-L1353) that can be used to generate old-style validators:    pre_FOO: function() {        return thisbuild_func(do_pre_FOO)()    }## PerformancePerformance on physical systems hasnt been affected very much however on virtual systems the runtime is now in line with what we expect for physical systemsPerformance measured with:time curl -k -u admin:admin https://localhost:8443/candlepin/owners/admin/poolsconsumer{UUID}### Virtual| master | this branch || ----- | ----- ||11314 | 6911 || 10487 | 5495 || 10714 | 5379 |### Physical|master | this branch || ----- | ----- |6344 | 61565538 | 54335494 | 5292## Final Notes[Am I doing this right](http://iimgurcom/ahFdEA7jpg)

Allow Candlepin To Run on FIPS server / JVM These changes allow Candlepin to run when configured on a server that is in FIPS mode as well as on a JVM that is in FIPS mode (default JCE provider set to SunPKCS11)A JVM can be put into FIPS mode by doing the following: http://blogjohnruizcom/2013/12/configure-fips-140-2-compliant-javahtml On Fedora 20 you may have keystore complaints on tomcat startup I have not figured out how to work around that yet but we suspect it can be done with keytool Some F20 systems did not encounter this issue It also appears that RHEL JDK 7 is using this JCE provider by defaultThe first change allows us to read a server CA PEM file which is in PKCS8  (unencrypted) form (which seems to be what is generated when you run our openssl setup commands on a FIPS enabled server) in addition to the PKCS1 format we generate/read normallyThe second change disables anonymous ECDH ciphers that probably never should have been in our tomcat config in the first place and adds a more secure ECDHE cipher More details in specific commit for thatUnable to come up with any logical ways to automate testing for these issues so no tests are included at this time

Fix mysql timestamps with liquibase  31 These two tables were being created with an incorrect column type forcreated/updated on mysql of timestamp without time zone (should be datetime)As of liquibase 31 the without time zone portion started being used andfailing due to incorrect syntax All other mysql tables use timestamp for thesecolumnsThis leaves us in a bad situation where some mysql databases (stage) have beencreated with incorrect column types and liquibase  31This patch attempts to correct both problems the original changesets aremodified to create the correct column type and the checksum fix isincorporated so existing mysql dbs will not complain about the changePostgres and oracle dbs do not see a changed checksum as their sql has notactually changedIf the changeset has already been applied incorrectly a subsequent mysql-onlychangeset will run that converts the column type to datetime If its alreadydatetime this should have no effectTested against master - this branch for a variety of combinations ofpostgres/mysql and liquibase versions everything should be working correctlynow

Ckozak/actkey overrides The consumer_id column in cp_consumer_content_override had a not null constraint which doesnt work anymore because it should be null when (and only when) key_id is not null  I dont think theres a way to have the database check that though  I dont think that check should be necessary thoughThe ContentOverrideResource class cannot use the @verify annotation because annotations cannot take variable parameters (the generic types in this case)  This is solved by requiring the implementing class (ConsumerContentOverrideResource for example) to define a findParentById method that looks up a Parent (Consumer in this case) using secure criteria such that an exception is thrown when the parent is not found which gives us the same result as the @verify annotation

RFC: Alikins/jks keystore This changes the deploy scripts and some cert gen scripts to use a JKS keystore by defaultThe main reasons for doing that are that keytool and other assorted tools dont like to import trusted certs into pkcs12 keystores For a self sign scenario this is okay But if we want to provide or generates a CA cert and thenimport it and use it to generate the tomcat/apache server cert with it we need to be able to import the trusted CA cert This also switches from generating and deploying a self signed server cert and instead generating a CA cert self signing that importing it into the keystore then using it to generate server certs This also creates a server cert specifically for tomcat that is imported into our keystore and another pem stylecertificate that we can use with mod_ssl/apache  (It should be possible to use the same cert for both with the appropriate format conversions/and or custom cert loading code but then there is also no particular need to use the same certificate)What this doesnt cover yet:- migrating pkcs12 keystores to jks keystores - Using a provided CA cert instead of generating a fresh one

Support filtering Pools by attribute Pool filtering by attribute can now be done by addingattribute query parameters to the request URIFor example:GET /owners/{owner_key}/poolsattributesupport_type:PremiumA @CandlepinParam can be added to a @QueryParam arguement definitionto customize the parsing of a parameteter Since attribute parametersare specified as attribute{attributeName}:{attributeValue} theattributes parameter is specified as follows:@QueryParam(attribute) @CandlepinParam(typeKeyValueParameterclass)This results in a list of KeyValueParameter objects that parse theattribute name/value from the value stringA FilterBuilder is then used to determine what attribute filters toapply to the criteria in the Curators The intent of this object isto allow further customizing filters without having to pass moreparams down to the curator level If you want more filteringcapabilities later on bolt it onto this objectThe current implementation follows the following filter rules:- parameters specifying the same attribute names will result in  an OR between values- parameters specifying different attibute names will result in an  AND between values- combinations are Ok between like/unlike attribute names and follow  the same rulesFor example consider:GET /owners/admin/poolsattributesupport_level:premium&attributesupport_level:none&attributesockets:4This results in:(support_level  premium OR none) AND sockets  4Value comparisons are NOT case sensitive and empty values are supportedNOTE: Filtering has been omitted from the PoolResource as it is depricated

Update auth system to allow my system administrators Overall goal is to allow user accounts which have permissions to manage only systems they registered (as based on the username stored during registration) Additionally we need to support this plus read-only access to the org where the user can also see other systems but cannot modify themThis required extensive changes to the auth system to allow more fine grained control The hacky READ_POOLS and READ_SUBSCRIPTIONS access level is replaced with the concept of a sub-resource so we can verify access to entities and also specify a sub-resource ie I can grant a permission for an Owner sub-resource Pools access level READ_ONLY to let consumers read pools in an org but not necessarily browse other systems in the orgThe system administrator permission introduced a new requirement where we only want to see certain consumers in a GET /owner/{key}/consumers those which match my username To accomplish this I added the ability for permissions to specify hibernate criteria restrictions to be added to the query before it is run This has the added benefit of letting pagination continue to work However the query filters add a lot of complexity where certain permissions can hide things from other permissions To solve this the permission filters are ORd together and the end result is that in general it is a good idea for permissions to include filters which show exactly what we expect that permission to be allowed to see OwnerPermission is the most likely place where this will surfaceThe dev/QE permissions system was expanded to allow us to store more than just one type of permission in our db previously we could only store OwnerPermission which would leave us unable to actually test this new system admin role Instead OwnerPermission became a non-persistent java class and a PermissionBlueprint was added which can be associated with a role and stored in our db This contains just enough information for the PermissionFactory to build the actual java class we wantThe trusted auth system was enhanced so a header can be specified which results in Candlepin calling back to the user service to actually ask for the permissions to add to the principal (previously it would only create principals with full access)Falling out of the use of filters we will usually see a 404 not found when asking for access to something the principal has no access to This reveals less information about what actually exists and prevents making API calls to gather information about what is out there 403 is still returned in some situations where we can see a resource we just cant perform the action were trying to performThe filters can be used via AbstractHibernateCuratorcreateSecureCriteria() When looking up specific objects by ID there are two methods one secure one not The unsecured one is still required as sometimes we must perform actions the principal technically cannot do (ie a virt_limit unbind means a pool needs to get deleted) When looking up by ID over the REST API you should see a 404 when you do not have permission Further down the stack we tend to use the insecure method of lookup by ID instead (See AuthInterceptor EntityStore implementations for where this happens)Fixed an issue where the Access level was stored in the db as a positional integer so code changes could change the meaning of what was storedAltered the pool deletion code and removed some strange things we were doing to deal with existence of duplicate attributes This was a very old problem which does not seem to exist any more (tested this myself and also note that we were not doing the strange things for derived product attributes and no problems have surfaced that were aware of) The strange code was causing hibernate errors when deleting a pool if we looked up the object with a query rather than a sessionget()

Generate candlepinconf based on a template and YAML data This patch adds a candlepin:erb task to buildr  When this task is run a candlepinconf file is auto-generated based on the template in the new erb directory  The template uses a set of standard defaults coupled with values defined in the new profilesyaml file and with values defined in customyaml  The customyaml file is not (and should not be) required by default (and it is in the gitignore file)  An example customyaml is below:candlepinconf:  custom_logging:     #orghibernateSQL: DEBUG    orgcandlepinservletfilter: DEBUG  additional_properties: |    log4jloggersomethingelseDEBUGThere are a few things to note  The first is that the first key in the YAML file must correspond to the file name of the rendered template  Secondly the custom_logging property takes a dictionary of class names and log levels  Appending a # to the class name will place the line in the rendered file but commented out  Finally any additional values can be specified by dropping them after the pipe symbol that follows the additional_properties keyPlease note that whitespace is important in YAML  See http://wwwyamlorg/YAML_for_rubyhtml and http://wwwyamlorg/refcardhtmlThe rendered template is placed in target/generated/erb/candlepinconfCopying the autogenerated file is incorporated in the buildconf/scripts/deploy script  You can either use the -a option with the script or set AUTOCONF1 in your candlepinrc file  The deploy script will not deploy the generated file if it does not detect the word AUTOGENERATED in the first line of candlepinconf  So to get the auto-deployment working you must bootstrap the process by editing candlepinconf to have the word AUTOGENERATED on the first line

DO NOT MERGE UNTIL TESTS ARE IN: 1004905: Do not allow hypercheckin to create hosts in different orgs THIS PATCH IS MISSING TESTS SUBMITTED SO THAT THE FUNCTIONALITYAND CODE COULD BE REVIEWED WHILE THE TESTS WERE BEING COMPLETEDIf multiple systems are reporting a host/guest mapping from thesame hypervisor it was possible that hosts can get created inmultiple orgs or appear that the update into the specified orgoccurred but did notFix Details------------ When checkin occurs via a Consumer principal:  * owner key now comes from the consumer  * if owner key is specified in the API call it must    match that of the consumer- When checkin occurs via a User principal:  * owner key must be specified  * user must have full access to the target org- When updating the host/guest mapping if ANY mapped host  exists and does not match the target owner we assume that  the checkin was already done and fail the transactionThis does allow multiple systems to do a checkin for the samehypervisor but restricts it to the same org

get javascript logging working with buildr Weve had a series of folks wanting to log from the rulesjs fileMaking changes to log4jproperties has proved to be useless I added-Dlog4jdebug to the jvm_args for testing to see what was going onand it turns out log4j was picking up the log4jproperties from:**GUICE-PERSIST**Theres a bug for that already:  https://codegooglecom/p/google-guice/issues/detailid623This does not affect the application because we forcibly configurelog4j in LoggingConfigjavaNo matter what we do buildr test will never pick up our log4jpropertiesI tried putting target/resources and target/classes at the front ofthe testwith classpath but that caused other problems like causingHibernate not to find any of the model classeslog4j will first look for a log4jxml file in the classpath if not foundthen looks for a log4jproperties file I investigated using a log4jxmlfile but it was quite ugly and difficult to use compared to the propertiesfile The alternative was to specify the properties file to use as ajvm_arg So I added a new log4j-testproperties to src/test/resourcesand defined it in the buildfile in the jvm_argIn order to see debug logging from javascript rules add thisto the new log4j-testproperties:  log4jloggerorgcandlepinpolicyjsDEBUG

Block physical binds with quantities not multiples of the instance multi plierEffectively if the instance multiplier is 2 and a physical consumer tries tobind with a quantity of say 3 or 5 They will receive an error message and thebind will be blocked The blocking occurs because physical systems consume poolsin increments of the multiplier in our current example 2Virt guests will not have this restriction They always consume the pools inincrements of 1We added a new preEntitlement(Consumer Pool Integer CallerType) method thatwill be called during bind and list pools This allows the rules to know whocalled them The other calls to preEntitlement continue to use the existingmethod which simply passes CallerTypeUNKNOWN to the new method This allows usto add new types in the future as we go along

make the next int more random A unit test failed on jenkins with this exception:javaxpersistencePersistenceException: orghibernateNonUniqueObjectException: a different object with the same identifier value was already associated with the session: [orgcandlepinmodelProduct#371]I tracked it down to the randomInt method causing duplicate ids to the point that running 1000 consecutive calls would result in 30-50 duplicate ids By simply calling nextInt without a bound and taking the absolute value of the result I got it down to 2 duplicates for 100000 consecutive runsHeres the test I used to verify it I didnt include it in the commit because it really isnt something I could consistently verify It could be 0 could be 1 sometimes it would hit 5 but most of the time it was 2    @Test    public void test() {        MapInteger Integer dupes  new HashMapInteger Integer()        ListInteger dupelist  new ArrayListInteger()        int[] ints  new int[100000]        for (int i  0 i  100000 i++) {            ints[i]  TestUtilrandomInt()            //Systemoutprintln(num:  + TestUtilrandomInt())        }        for (int i : ints) {            if (dupescontainsKey(i)) {                dupesput(i i)            }            else {                dupelistadd(i)            }        }        Systemoutprintln(There are  + dupelistsize() +  duplicate ids)    }http://hudsonrhqlabengbosredhatcom:8080/hudson/view/chainsaw/job/candlepin-unittest/69/testReport/junit/orgcandlepinmodeltest/OwnerInfoCuratorTest/testOwnerPoolEnabledZeroCount/

Refactor for each  into ArrayforEach The for each statement is not part of the ECMAScript standard as such itsnot supported by all major javascript engines (such as Googles V8)  Its alsobeen deprecated to discourage its use  Seehttps://developermozillaorg/en-US/docs/JavaScript/Reference/Statements/for_eachinfor more informationThis patch refactors its usage into ArrayforEachI believe this should create equivalent functionality each time  If you see any issues let me know and I could look into updating those occurrences to something different

Wottop/manifest import update Previous method used upstream pool id in existing subscription to match with new entitlementsThe possibility of having multiple entitlements from the same upstream pool makes this error proneNew method will first match upstream pool and entitlement id from incoming entitlementsNext it will match upstream pool and exact quantity to cover scenarios where the intent is to re-establish the distributor from the hostIt will then match using the quantity by ordering the remaining incoming entitlements and remaining existing subscriptions in descending orderThe highest will match on down from thereEither remaining subscriptions will be deleted or unmatched incoming entitlements will be turned into new subscriptions

887287: Detect when virt_limit is removed from subscriptions We now detect this scenario by comparing the incoming latest attributesfor a product against the cached attributes on the pool beingrefreshed If we see virt_limit has disappeared we signal to candlepinthat the pool should be cleaned up Because old candlepins will nothave this functionality we also set the expected quantity to 0 toeffectively disable it on those servers as wellThis mechanism for the js rules to signal to candlepin that somethingshould be done is a new idea but one that might help us get around theissues we have where we cannot add new functionality/variables to therules as it would break on old candlepins At least with this scenariothe behavior is not implemented but no errors will occur when used onan old serverThis does not include support for detecting when virt_limit has been*added* to a product and creating the necessary bonus pool This will behandled as a separate bug due to time contraints

886211: Fix a deadlock in mysql Appears to be an issue with deadlocks when deleting a consumeroriginating in the listModifying routine Verified that the bug inquestion was not *actually* using modifier entitlements just the simpleact of looking for them across entitlements which were already deletedcaused a deadlock on mysqlWe dont need to do this when mass deleting entitlements because aconsumer was deleted so disable this functionality when theentitlements are getting revoked anyhowMade method in question package protected so @Transactional continues towork as it was only used by other methods in the classUsed the one line from revokeEntitlement inside revokeAllEntitlementsthis prevents the regenModified parameter from leaking up into theinterface and around the code when really it should be transparentlyhandled just by using the revoke/removeAll methods

Overconsumption check performance fix Following a bind we check all pools that potentially may have beenmodified during the bind to see if any are now oversubscribed Currentlythis is just to accomodate hosted binds to virt_limit pools when theconsumer is a manifest consumer In this future this is probably goingto be used in other cases as wellOn-site with virt bonus pools we were looking at ~10k entitlementsfrom a virt_limit pool plus one pool per entitlement for the hostrestricted guest pools This resulted in gradual performancedegredation at the 10k mark a bind was taking about 20sUsing some knowledge of what pools could actually be changed as theresult of a bind (or a modify entitlement quantity) we know that weonly need to check pools where the source entitlement is null (ie virtbonus pools in hosted at most 2) or the source entitlement is theentitlement being granted/modified (at most 1) This cuts a massiveamount of data churn down to just a max of around 2 pools and eliminates90% of the time spent in the bind operationAfter this bind should not experience any degredation as the number ofentitlements to the pool growsConflicts:src/main/java/org/candlepin/controller/CandlepinPoolManagerjava

Ignore old rules in database after a Candlepin upgrade We were correctly catching incoming old rules during manifest importsand ignoring them in favor of those included in our rpm We were nothandling old rules in the database after a candlepin upgrade howeverleading to major failures as we tried to use old rules that didnt workon the new CandlepinAdded a column in the rules table for the candlepin version the rulesoriginated from This is set on import as well as during a manualupload (to the current version of candlepin)When requesting the rules we check if the version in the database isolder than our current version and ignore it if so If we see a nullcandlepin version in the db we know these must be older than the codewere runningConstructor updated to try to make sure we dont mistakenly store ruleswithout specifying that Candlepin version

Add new mechanism for detecting/overriding import conflicts Added several new types of manifest import conflicts which can beoverridden by the caller On import 409 responses will also includeprogramatic keys which other projects can use to distinguish why theimport failed The request can be retried with a multi-valued forceparameter to overrideforcetrue will behave as it did before ignoring an older manifestcreation date and importing anyhowAdded distributor conflicts which allow the caller to link their org toa new upstream distributor (should they have deleted it accidentallyetc) This may cause drastic changes to their subscriptions but not ifused for a new distributor in the same upstream org and using the samepoolsSignature checking code is brought back but disabled until otherprojects are ready for itWe also now distinguish between an older manifest and the same manifestcurrently imported

800145: Update pools across all owners on product import Previously upon importing an export file if a product was modifiedwe would regenerate the certificates of all entitlements that referencedthat product We would then run a refreshPools on the owner thatimported the export the refreshPools would adjust that owners pools toreflect the new product attributes but not any other ownersThat was the intention anyways In reality the code to look forchanged products compared the new forms of the products to the productsfrom the db but only after it had already updated the db Thus theproducts were never found to have changed and no certs wereregeneratedThis patch fixes that up by comparing the new forms of the products withthe form as it is in the db before storing the new form Further itcorrects the code to check for changes catching more instances when theproducts are differentTo refresh the pools referencing the affected products but also ensurethat a pool that references two products or a pool that is owned by theimporting owner is not refreshed multiple times introduce a newRefresher object that takes care of gathering up the objects we want totrigger a refresh on (products owners) then executes the poolrefreshes and entitlement regens without repeating anythingThe existing code to trigger a refresh by product was being overly broadon what pools it would refresh (triggering for all pools for an ownerthat had a single pool that referenced the product rather than just thereferencing pools) This patch also narrows the focus down to just theaffected pools and introduces a spec test to verify that

Macro SUMMARY-----------------Adding ability to build with candlepin-deps or real BuildRequires from a single candlepinspec This also allows us to build a community release for EL6TEST-------You will need the **LATEST** tito from master: https://githubcom/dgoodwin/tito* Get the latest tito git clone git@githubcom:dgoodwin/titogit* Build the latest from master and install it: tito build --test --rpm -iNow you can test this pull request* Create temporary directory: mkdir /tmp/rheltest* In the [yum-rhel-x86_64] section comment out the existing rsync config entry in rel-eng/releasersconf* Add rsync  /tmp/rheltest to rel-eng/releasersconf* Save the fileWhy did you do that you dont want your test to end up on the live repo but we want it to do something So setting the rsync target to a local temporary directory is a good way of verifying things worked* **BE CAREFUL FOLLOW CLOSELY*** Tag the branch (youll be undoing this in a couple steps): tito tag --offline* Use mock to release a EL6 version using candlepin-deps: tito release --offline yum-rhel-x86_64* **IMPORTANT** Undo the tag: tito tag -u* Now ls /tmp/rheltest should reveal the newly built candlepin* DONE

Add ability to remove a cert from the certificate revocation list (CRL) Quite a bit of refactoring had to occur and a few bug fixes in the process* CrlGenerator:  * Renamed updateCRL to syncCRLWithDB  * removed createCRL() which was useless  * added removeEntries(X509CRL ListCertificateSerial)* CertificateSerialCurator  * added listBySerialIds method* BouncyCastlePKIUtility  * added warning suppression because of all the YELLOW warnings* CrlResource  * new unrevoke() method that takes in a list of certificate serial ids* CertifiateRevocationListTask  * simplified the logic a bit: readCRL sync writefile* CRLFileUtil  * broke apart the updateCRL method into more meaningful methods  * added X509CRL readCRLFile(File) to read in the contents of the    existing crl (or return an empty one)  * added byte[] writeCRLFile(File X509CRL) which will write the given    CRL to the given File and return a PEM encoded copy of the CRL in    case the callers needs it for any reasonTESTING---------------To test this do the following:* register a consumer to candlepin* Subscribe it to a pool* Take note of the entitlement number: ls /etc/pki/entitlements/*pem (youll need it later)* Get your consumer uuid* Delete the entitlements for that consumer:  curl -k -u admin:admin -X DELETE https://localhost:8443/candlepin/consumers/UUID/entitlements/* get the current CRL to see how many records are there  curl -k -u admin:admin https://localhost:8443/candlepin/crl  currentcrl  Using openssl crl -text -in currentcrl you can verify our certificate is in the crl*  Now remove the cert serial from the CRL:curl -k -u admin:admin -X DELETE https://localhost:8443/candlepin/crl/sidENTITLEMENT_ID_FROM_ABOVE* get the current CRL to see how many records are there  curl -k -u admin:admin https://localhost:8443/candlepin/crl  newcrl  Using openssl crl -text -in newcrl you can verify our certificate is in the crl
